@Ahmad and skeleton Thanks, haha. After a long hiatus and chatting with a few pals on Reddit, I came back to this topic with a conclusion. Games nowadays are padded with meaningless content to make you feel like it was "worth it" to pay for it. As in, people started to complain that they paid 50 USD for a game that lasted 20 - 40 hours. As games developed and became increasingly expensive (motion capture, cgi, soundtracks), they had to compensate for the price, advertising "hundreds" of hours of gameplay and content.

I'm not saying this happens with all games, of course. But in most of them, you have a single player campaign that lasts 20 hours and 250 hours of meaningless, padding or lame sidequests that gives you a shallow experience.

There is also the factor that videogames stopped being developed by gamers for gamers, (and also as a medium of art), and started being developed by businessmen to make money.

